        "client_msg_id": "3b9041b3-5745-416d-ae7d-f71e19245a2c",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "A challenge with going after a title like \"chief content officer\" (and this role in the traditional, so called C-suite) is that \"officer\" has a binding legal meaning in a way that rank-signifying titles like \"manager\" or \"director\" or even \"vice president\" don't. An officer is theoretically (and usually in practice) someone who is approved by the shareholders and\/or board to execute contracts and generally act unilaterally on behalf of the company. So a traditional role like CFO exists to allow a trusted finance expert to sign as the company when dealing with the IRS, for instance.",
